At Savoy, they talk a lot about being one with the stream of timelessness. Makes you think about true restaurant legacies. 
When it opened in 1937, Finnish nationalism was rising, and Savoy wanted to set new fine dining standards. The front-of-house rules were a template for today's best practices: servers should know the menu well, regulars were to be respected, breadcrumbs were not to be seen on tables, and liquors were always to be served in cold glasses.

But the thing that really immortalized Savoy was its design, overlooking Helsinki. Architects Alvar and Aino Aalto created a room of clean lines, natural light and birch finishes ... And, on every table, the now-famous ‚Äî and timeless ‚Äî Aalto vase. (Food's overpriced though.) #design #helsinki #aalto  #history #restaurant
